After version 1:
We used a stride-based approach, basically take every Nth scan and skip the rest. For example stride=10 means we keep scan 0, skip 1-9, keep 10, skip 11-19, etc. This is why we ended up with ~16% of the full data.

To avoid losing rare classes (cyclists, pedestrians, motorcyclists), scans containing those classes are sampled more frequently using a smaller rare_stride:
Train: stride=10, rare_stride=8
Val: stride=10, rare_stride=6
Test: stride=12, rare_stride=10

If anyone wants to experiment, the easiest way to get more data is just reducing the stride values. For example changing train stride from 10 → 6 and rare_stride from 8 → 4 would roughly double the dataset size. Would be interesting to see if that improves mIoU! also try to play with the hyperparameters to see if it gives better results
--------------------------------

Got it running on Colab with our subsampled dataset (12GB total - train+test+val) and got 44.7% val mIoU at 200 epochs. Current dataset breakdown: 2,913 train scans + 871 val scans (3,784 total) out of the full 23,201 train+val scans SemanticKITTI scans - roughly 15% of the full dataset.

Hyperparameters used: batch size 6, val batch size 4, epoch steps 100, val steps 100. The gap from the 58.8% baseline is mostly due to less data, scaled-down hyperparameters, and not yet reaching the full 800 epochs (official uses batch size 12, epoch steps 500, val steps 200).

Next:
Keep training toward 800 epochs
Increase train + val data to ~15GB (keeping test set untouched)
Run inference on test sequences 11-21
Once hit a reasonable mIoU, experiment with other models like KPConvX

Some observations:
epoch=10, epoch step=10, val step=50
val mIoU - 15-20%
epoch=100, epoch step=100, val step=100
val mIoU - 33%
epoch=200, epoch step=100, val step=100
val mIoU - 44.7%
